","1306":"1306年","Lankarkshire, Scotland":"苏格兰","Humbie, Haddingtonshire, Scotland":"苏格兰哈丁頓史爾比","Keith, East Lothian, Scotland":"苏格兰班福爾凱斯","Scotland":"苏格兰","lifeSummary":"当Richard de Keith于1225年出生在苏格兰时，他的父亲Hervey de Keith, Marischal of Scotland39岁，母亲Margaret de Douglas47岁。他于1245年之前与Lady Richard de Keith在苏格兰结婚。他们至少是2个儿子的父母。他去世于1255年在他的家乡享年30岁，埋葬在苏格兰。"},"hr":{"1225–1255":"1225.–1255.","1212–1270":"1212–1270","1230–Female":"1230–preminula","1245–Male":"1245–preminuo","1247–1306":"1247.–1306","1187–1250":"1187–1250","1178–1260":"1178–1260","before 1245":"prije 1245.","1187":"1187","1230":"1230","1250":"1250","1260":"1260","1270":"1270","1225":"1225.","1247":"1247.","1245":"1245","1212":"1212","1255":"1255.","1178":"1178","about 1245":"oko 1245.","before 1250":"prije 1250.","1306":"1306","Lankarkshire, Scotland":"Scotland","Humbie, Haddingtonshire, Scotland":"Humbie, Haddingtonshire, Scotland","Keith, East Lothian, Scotland":"Keith, Banffshire, Scotland","Scotland":"Scotland"},"cs":{"1225–1255":"1225–1255","1212–1270":"1212–1270","1230–Female":"1230–Zesnulá","1245–Male":"1245–Zesnulý","1247–1306":"1247–1306","1187–1250":"1187–1250","1178–1260":"1178–1260","before 1245":"před 1245","1187":"1187","1230":"1230","1250":"1250","1260":"1260","1270":"1270","1225":"1225","1247":"1247","1245":"1245","1212":"1212","1255":"1255","1178":"1178","about 1245":"okolo 1245","before 1250":"před 1250","1306":"1306","Lankarkshire, Scotland":"Scotland","Humbie, Haddingtonshire, Scotland":"Humbie, Haddingtonshire, Scotland","Keith, East Lothian, Scotland":"Keith, Banffshire, Scotland","Scotland":"Scotland"},"da":{"1225–1255":"1225–1255","1212–1270":"1212–1270","1230–Female":"1230–Afdød","1245–Male":"1245–Afdød","1247–1306":"1247–1306","1187–1250":"1187–1250","1178–1260":"1178–1260","before 1245":"før 1245","1187":"1187","1230":"1230","1250":"1250","1260":"1260","1270":"1270","1225":"1225","1247":"1247","1245":"1245","1212":"1212","1255":"1255","1178":"1178","about 1245":"omkring 1245","before 1250":"før 1250","1306":"1306","Lankarkshire, Scotland":"Skotland","Humbie, Haddingtonshire, Scotland":"Humbie, Haddingtonshire, Skotland","Keith, East Lothian, Scotland":"Keith, Banffshire, Skotland","Scotland":"Skotland"},"nl":{"1225–1255":"1225–1255","1212–1270":"1212–1270","1230–Female":"1230–Overleden","1245–Male":"1245–Overleden","1247–1306":"1247–1306","1187–1250":"1187–1250","1178–1260":"1178–1260","before 1245":"vóór 1245","1187":"1187","1230":"1230","1250":"1250","1260":"1260","1270":"1270","1225":"1225","1247":"1247","1245":"1245","1212":"1212","1255":"1255","1178":"1178","about 1245":"circa 1245","before 1250":"vóór 1250","1306":"1306","Lankarkshire, Scotland":"Schotland","Humbie, Haddingtonshire, Scotland":"Humbie, Haddingtonshire, Schotland","Keith, East Lothian, Scotland":"Keith, Banffshire, Schotland","Scotland":"Schotland"},"en":{"1225–1255":"1225–1255","1212–1270":"1212–1270","1230–Female":"1230–Deceased","1245–Male":"1245–Deceased","1247–1306":"1247–1306","1187–1250":"1187–1250","1178–1260":"1178–1260","before 1245":"before 1245","1187":"1187","1230":"1230","1250":"1250","1260":"1260","1270":"1270","1225":"1225","1247":"1247","1245":"1245","1212":"1212","1255":"1255","1178":"1178","about 1245":"about 1245","before 1250":"before 1250","1306":"1306","Lankarkshire, Scotland":"Scotland","Humbie, Haddingtonshire, Scotland":"Humbie, Haddingtonshire, Scotland","Keith, East Lothian, Scotland":"Keith, Banffshire, Scotland","Scotland":"Scotland","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Keith","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish: habitational name from the lands of Keith in East Lothian. The placename is derived from British Celtic <i>cait-</i> ‘wood’. In the 17th century numerous bearers of this name settled in Ulster.","German: nickname from Middle High German <i>kīt</i> ‘sprout, offspring’.","History: George Keith (<i>c.</i> 1638–1716), born at Peterhead, Aberdeenshire, Scotland, came to NJ in or before 1685. In 1689 he settled in Philadelphia, where he became headmaster of the school now called the William Penn Charter School. He came into sharp collision with the Quaker leaders in PA and formed a separatist party known as the Christian Quakers, popularly known as ‘Keithians’."],"variants":[{"name":"Kight","meanings":["Americanized form of German   Keith  .","English: perhaps a variant of   Kite  ."]},{"name":"Keath","meanings":["Scottish and English (mainly Cambridgeshire): variant of   Keith  ."]},{"name":"Kite","meanings":["English: nickname from Middle English <i>kete</i>, <i>kyte</i> ‘kite’ (the bird of prey), perhaps a nickname for a rapacious person.","Americanized form of German   Keith  .","English: habitational name from one or more of the minor places with names deriving from Old English <i>cȳte</i>, <i>cyte</i> ‘cottage, hut, shed’, such as Kite Farm in Swalecliffe (Kent)."]},{"name":"Keeth","meanings":["English and Scottish: variant of   Keith  ."]},{"name":"Keitt","meanings":["Possibly an altered form of German   Keith   2."]}]},{"name":"Richard","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Rikert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]},{"name":"Rickert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Richard de Keith was born in 1225, in Scotland, his father, Hervey de Keith, Marischal of Scotland, was 39 and his mother, Margaret de Douglas, was 47. He married Lady Richard de Keith before 1245, in Scotland. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. He died in 1255, in his hometown, at the age of 30, and was buried in Scotland."},"et":{"1225–1255":"1225–1255","1212–1270":"1212–1270","1230–Female":"1230–Surnud","1245–Male":"1245–Surnud","1247–1306":"1247–1306","1187–1250":"1187–1250","1178–1260":"1178–1260","before 1245":"enne 1245","1187":"1187","1230":"1230","1250":"1250","1260":"1260","1270":"1270","1225":"1225","1247":"1247","1245":"1245","1212":"1212","125